default3.1
default              
defaultThe Commission has specific statutory duties and powers to enforce the 
default              
defaultequality enactments and to work towards the elimination of unlawful 
default              
defaultdiscrimination and harassment (under section 8 Equality Act 2006). 
default3.2
default              
defaultOur approach to exercising our statutory functions is to enable duty-holders to 
default              
defaultcomply with the legislation and take enforcement action only where it is 
default              
defaultnecessary and proportionate to do so to ensure legal compliance in practice.
default3.3
default              
defaultThe Equality Act 2010 represents the main domestic equality enactment over 
default              
defaultwhich the Commission has a guardianship role as a statutory enforcer. That 
default              
defaultguardianship role can be exercised in part by issuing codes of practice and 
default              
defaultguidance to improve understanding of rights and obligations and to support 
default              
defaultlegal compliance. It also encompasses use of specific legal powers - such as 
default              
defaultholding inquiries, carrying out investigations, or supporting litigation through 
default              
defaultcourts and tribunals - to identify and challenge non-compliance. 
default3.4
default              
defaultUK equality law has been proposed by Government, scrutinised and enacted 
default              
defaultby Parliament and is interpreted by tribunals and courts. One of the general 
default              
defaultaims and principles underpinning the legislation is that prevention of 
default              
defaultdiscrimination is preferable to remedy after the event, and this is supported by 
default              
defaultsections 124 and 149 of the Equality Act 2010. That Act had broad cross-party 
default              
defaultpolitical support during its Parliamentary passage. 
default3.5
default              
defaultTo complement the judicial system (without acting as a substitute for it), the 
default              
defaultCommission carries out follow-up work to ensure tribunal recommendations 
default              
defaulthave been carried out in practice. 
default3.6
default              
defaultIn August 2012 the Commission responded to the Government's consultation, 
default              
defaulton proposals that included the removal of employment tribunals’ wider 
default              
defaultrecommendations power. Our reasons for opposing the removal of this power 
default              
defaultwere:
default&#xa0;
default3.7
default              
defaultThe Commission still believes that the ability to make "wider" 
default              
defaultrecommendations is an important one which should be retained. Its removal 
default              
defaultwould limit the powers of tribunals to make recommendations to those cases 
default              
defaultwhere the recommendations would alleviate the discrimination only for an 
default              
defaultindividual claimant.
default So long as the current recommendations are followed, the 
default              
defaultexercise of the power benefits:
